        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>691</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-002J</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-002J.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hilbert Space">Hilbert Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Hilbert space is a complete <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002M.xml" addr="FA-002M" title="Inner Product">inner product space</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Hilbert spaces extend the methods of vector algebra and calculus from 2D and 3D Euclidean spaces to spaces with any finite or infinite number of dimensions.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Key properties include:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Every Hilbert space is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002I.xml" addr="FA-002I" title="Banach Space">Banach space</fr:link>, with the norm derived from the inner product</fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-002N.xml" addr="FA-002N" title="Orthonormal Basis">Orthonormal basis</fr:link> existence</fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-002O.xml" addr="FA-002O" title="Projection Theorem">Projection theorem</fr:link></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>693</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001Y</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001Y.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hölder inequality">Hölder inequality</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f, g : E \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable functions</fr:link>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p, q \in  [1, +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001W.xml" addr="FA-001W" title="Conjugate exponents">conjugate</fr:link>. Then</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[||fg||_{L^1(E)} \leq  ||f||_{L^p(E)} ||g||_{L^q(E)}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>The proof uses <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001X.xml" addr="FA-001X" title="Young's Inequality">Young's Inequality</fr:link></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Remark</fr:strong> Hölder inequality can be also rephrased as follows:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\int _E |f(x)|^\alpha  |g(x)|^\beta  dx \leq  \left (\int _E |f(x)| dx\right )^\alpha  \left (\int _E |g(x)| dx\right )^\beta ]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>provided <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha  + \beta  = 1]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Discrete case</fr:strong> Let</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = (x_1, \dots , x_n), y = (y_1, \dots , y_n) \in  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p, q \in  {1,2,3 \dots }]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1/p + 1/q = 1]]></fr:tex>, then</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\sum _{i=1}^n |x_i y_i| \leq  \left (\sum _{i=1}^n |x_i|^p\right )^{1/p} \left (\sum _{i=1}^n |y_i|^q\right )^{1/q}]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>694</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-003V</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-003V.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lebesgue Measure">Lebesgue Measure</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>When we say something is "<fr:link type="local" href="FA-003C.xml" addr="FA-003C" title="Measurable Set">measurable</fr:link>", we often mean <fr:strong>Lebesgue measurable</fr:strong>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Lebesgue measure is the standard way of assigning a measure to subsets of Euclidean space. It extends the classical notion of length, area, and volume from simple shapes to a larger class of sets.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The Lebesgue measure on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> is constructed by first defining the measure for intervals or rectangles, then extending it to more general sets through <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003W.xml" addr="FA-003W" title="Lebesgue Outer Measure">outer measure</fr:link> and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003X.xml" addr="FA-003X" title="Lebesgue Inner Measure">inner measure</fr:link> techniques.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>696</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001E</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001E.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem">Lebesgue's Dominated Convergence Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_k : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [-\infty , +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> be a sequence of measurable functions. Suppose that</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li>There exists a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001L.xml" addr="FA-001L" title="Measurable function">measurable function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [-\infty , +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_n \to  f]]></fr:tex> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost everywhere</fr:link>.</fr:li>
<fr:li>There exists a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001M.xml" addr="FA-001M" title="Summable">summable</fr:link> function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g : \mathbb {R}^d \to  [-\infty , +\infty ]]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f_n(x)| \leq  g(x)]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> and for <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001D.xml" addr="FA-001D" title="Almost everywhere">almost every</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  \mathbb {R}^d]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ol>
            <fr:p>Then,</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[{\int  f(x)dx = \lim _{n \to  +\infty } \int  f_n(x)dx}]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>698</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-003B</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-003B.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Lp norm">Lp norm</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p < +\infty ]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \Omega  \subset  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> be a Lebesgue <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003C.xml" addr="FA-003C" title="Measurable Set">measurable set</fr:link>. For a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003D.xml" addr="FA-003D" title="Measurable Function">measurable function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: \Omega  \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> we define the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \Omega ]]></fr:tex> as the (finite or infinite) number:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{||f||_{L^p(\Omega )} \stackrel {\text {def}}{=} \left (\int _{\Omega } |f(x)|^p dx\right )^{1/p}}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>Moreover, we set:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{C \stackrel {\text {def}}{=} \{\alpha  \in  \mathbb {R} : |f(x)| \leq  \alpha  \text { almost everywhere on } \Omega \}.}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex> norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> (also called the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003E.xml" addr="FA-003E" title="Essential Supremum">essential supremum</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>) is defined as:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{||f||_{L^\infty (\Omega )} = \inf  C}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>700</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-003C</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-003C.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Measurable Set">Measurable Set</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:em>bounded</fr:em> subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E \subset  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:strong>Lebesgue <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0142">measurable</fr:link></fr:strong> if:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{m^*(E) = m_*(E)}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m^*(E)]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003W.xml" addr="FA-003W" title="Lebesgue Outer Measure">Lebesgue outer measure</fr:link> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m_*(E)]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003X.xml" addr="FA-003X" title="Lebesgue Inner Measure">Lebesgue inner measure</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>unbounded</fr:em> we say that E is <fr:strong>Lebesgue <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0142">measurable</fr:link></fr:strong> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E \cap  B_R(0)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:strong>Lebesgue <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0142">measurable</fr:link></fr:strong> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R \geq  0]]></fr:tex> and set:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{m(E) = \lim _{R \to  +\infty  }{m(E \cap  B_R(0))}}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m(E)]]></fr:tex> may be <fr:em>infinite</fr:em>!</fr:p>
            <fr:p>These concepts satisfy <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0143">Boolean closure</fr:link>:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>The empty set is <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0142">measurable</fr:link> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m(\emptyset ) = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0142">measurable</fr:link> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m(\mathbb {R}^n) = +\infty ]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Fact</fr:strong>: The <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003V.xml" addr="FA-003V" title="Lebesgue Measure">Lebesgue measure</fr:link> is <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0144">translation invariant</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>702</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-003D</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-003D.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Measurable Function">Measurable Function</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>These are all equivalent definitions of <fr:strong>measurable functions</fr:strong>:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \alpha  \in  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \left \{ x \in  \Omega : f(x) > \alpha  \right \}]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable</fr:li>
  <fr:li>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \alpha  \in  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \left \{ x \in  \Omega : f(x) < \alpha  \right \}]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable</fr:li>
  <fr:li>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \alpha  \in  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \left \{ x \in  \Omega : f(x) \geq  \alpha  \right \}]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable</fr:li>
  <fr:li>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \alpha  \in  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \left \{ x \in  \Omega : f(x) \leq  \alpha  \right \}]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable</fr:li>
  <fr:li>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U \subset  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ \left \{ x \in  \Omega : f(x) \in  U \right \}]]></fr:tex> is Lebesgue measurable</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>704</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-002P</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-002P.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Metric Space">Metric Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A metric space is a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> equipped with a <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0116">distance measure</fr:link> (or metric) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d: X \times  X \rightarrow  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> that satisfies the following properties for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x, y, z \in  X]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, y) \geq  0]]></fr:tex> (non-negativity)</fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, y) = 0]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = y]]></fr:tex> (identity of indiscernibles)</fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, y) = d(y, x)]]></fr:tex> (symmetry)</fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, z) \leq  d(x, y) + d(y, z)]]></fr:tex> (triangle inequality)</fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Metric spaces provide a general framework for studying concepts like <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0117">convergence</fr:link>, <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0118">continuity</fr:link>, and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002Q.xml" addr="FA-002Q" title="Completeness">completeness</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002K.xml" addr="FA-002K" title="Normed Space">normed space</fr:link> is a metric space with the metric defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, y) = |x - y|]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>706</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-002S</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-002S.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Norm">Norm</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Important concepts:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-003F.xml" addr="FA-003F" title="Operator Norm">operator norm</fr:link></fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-003G.xml" addr="FA-003G" title="Sup Norm">sup norm</fr:link></fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-003B.xml" addr="FA-003B" title="Lp norm">Lp norm</fr:link></fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:link type="external" href="FA-0125">C1 norm</fr:link>, or in general <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C^p]]></fr:tex>-norm</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>708</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-003F</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-003F.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Operator Norm">Operator Norm</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The operator norm is a type of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002S.xml" addr="FA-002S" title="Norm">norm</fr:link> defined for <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002G.xml" addr="FA-002G" title="Bounded Linear Operator">bounded linear operators</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002G.xml" addr="FA-002G" title="Bounded Linear Operator">bounded linear operator</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T: X \rightarrow  Y]]></fr:tex> between <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002K.xml" addr="FA-002K" title="Normed Space">normed spaces</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, the operator norm is defined as:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{||T|| = \sup _{x \neq  0} \frac {||Tx||_Y}{||x||_X} = \sup _{||x||_X=1} ||Tx||_Y}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>This norm measures the maximum "stretching factor" of the operator, i.e., how much the operator can amplify the length of a unit vector.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Key properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>A linear operator is <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0131">bounded</fr:link> if and only if it has a finite operator norm</fr:li>
  <fr:li>For operators <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ ||S \circ  T|| \leq  ||S|| \cdot  ||T||]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
  <fr:li>The set of bounded linear operators from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B(X,Y)]]></fr:tex>, forms a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002I.xml" addr="FA-002I" title="Banach Space">Banach space</fr:link> when equipped with the operator norm</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>710</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-002O</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-002O.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Projection Theorem">Projection Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> be a closed subspace of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002J.xml" addr="FA-002J" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>. Then for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex>, there exists a unique element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m \in  M]]></fr:tex> such that:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\ |x - m| = \inf _{y \in  M} |x - y|]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>Furthermore:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> is the unique element in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x - m]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0110">orthogonal</fr:link> to every element in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
  <fr:li>The mapping <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_M: H \rightarrow  M]]></fr:tex> defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_M(x) = m]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002H.xml" addr="FA-002H" title="Linear Operator">linear operator</fr:link> called the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0033.xml" addr="FA-0033" title="Orthogonal Projection">orthogonal projection</fr:link> onto <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>This theorem establishes the existence of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0034.xml" addr="FA-0034" title="Projection">projection</fr:link> operator in Hilbert spaces, which has fundamental importance in functional analysis.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>712</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0001</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0001.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Weierstrass approximation theorem">Weierstrass approximation theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The set of polynomials on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[a, b]]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0002.xml" addr="FA-0002" title="Dense">dense</fr:link> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C([a, b])]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>Differs from Taylor's theorem, which states that a function with sufficiently many derivaties can be approximated locally by its <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0003.xml" addr="FA-0003" title="Taylor polynomial">Taylor polynomial</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The Weierstrass appoximation theorem applied to a continuous function, which need not be differentiable, and states that there exists a global polynomial approximation of the function on the whole interval <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[a,b]]]></fr:tex> (The sequence of approximating polynomials is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0004.xml" addr="FA-0004" title="Bernstein polynomials">Bernstein polynomials</fr:link>)</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
</fr:tree>
